hook.real_world_problem:
A user places an order. Your API needs to:
1. Save the order to the database (50ms)
2. Send a confirmation email (1-3 seconds — network call)
3. Notify the warehouse system (500ms — another network call)
4. Return 201 Created to the user

**Blocking approach** — user waits 4+ seconds:
```java
@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<Order> placeOrder(@RequestBody OrderRequest req) {
    Order saved = orderService.save(req);   // 50ms
    emailSvc.sendConfirmation(saved);       // 2000ms — user WAITING
    warehouseSvc.notify(saved);             // 500ms — user STILL WAITING
    return ResponseEntity.status(201).body(saved);  // finally!
}
// Total: ~2550ms per order. With 100 concurrent orders: thread pool exhausted.
```

**@Async approach** — user gets 201 in 60ms:
```java
@Service
class NotificationService {
    @Async  // runs in a background thread pool
    public void sendConfirmation(Order order) {
        emailSvc.send(order.getUserEmail(), buildEmail(order));
        // 2 seconds — but the HTTP thread is LONG GONE by now
    }

    @Async
    public void notifyWarehouse(Order order) {
        warehouseSvc.notify(order);
    }
}

@PostMapping
public ResponseEntity<Order> placeOrder(@RequestBody OrderRequest req) {
    Order saved = orderService.save(req);        // 50ms
    notificationSvc.sendConfirmation(saved);     // returns immediately!
    notificationSvc.notifyWarehouse(saved);      // returns immediately!
    return ResponseEntity.status(201).body(saved);  // 60ms total
}
// The notifications run in background. User is happy. Throughput is high.
```

concept_explanation.enable_async:
**Enabling @Async in Spring Boot:**

```java
import org.springframework.scheduling.annotation.EnableAsync;

@SpringBootApplication
@EnableAsync  // activates @Async support — add this to your main class
public class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) { SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args); }
}
```

**Or in a configuration class:**
```java
@Configuration
@EnableAsync
public class AsyncConfig {
    // optionally configure the executor here
}
```

Without `@EnableAsync`, the `@Async` annotation is silently ignored — methods run synchronously. Always add `@EnableAsync` when using `@Async`.

concept_explanation.async_usage:
**@Async — fire-and-forget background tasks:**

```java
@Service
public class NotificationService {

    // Void @Async: fire-and-forget, no return value:
    @Async
    public void sendWelcomeEmail(String email, String username) {
        // Runs in Spring's async thread pool
        // The calling thread returns immediately — this continues in background
        try {
            emailClient.send(email, "Welcome, " + username + "!");
            System.out.println("Email sent to " + email + " on thread: "
                + Thread.currentThread().getName());
        } catch (Exception e) {
            // IMPORTANT: exceptions in void @Async methods are lost!
            // Use an AsyncUncaughtExceptionHandler or log here
            log.error("Failed to send email to " + email, e);
        }
    }

    // CompletableFuture @Async: caller can wait for result if needed:
    @Async
    public CompletableFuture<String> generateReport(String userId) {
        // Long-running operation — runs in background
        String report = reportBuilder.build(userId);  // takes 5 seconds
        return CompletableFuture.completedFuture(report);
    }
}

// In a service or controller:
notificationService.sendWelcomeEmail(user.getEmail(), user.getName()); // returns immediately!
// OR wait for the result:
CompletableFuture<String> reportFuture = notificationService.generateReport(userId);
// Do other work...
String report = reportFuture.get(30, TimeUnit.SECONDS);  // wait up to 30s
```

**Critical rule**: `@Async` only works when the method is called from OUTSIDE the class (via the Spring proxy). `this.sendEmail()` from within the same class bypasses the proxy — @Async is ignored.

concept_explanation.async_executor:
**Custom thread pool configuration:**

```java
import org.springframework.scheduling.concurrent.ThreadPoolTaskExecutor;

@Configuration
@EnableAsync
public class AsyncConfig {

    @Bean(name = "notificationExecutor")
    public Executor notificationExecutor() {
        ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
        executor.setCorePoolSize(5);         // always 5 threads running
        executor.setMaxPoolSize(20);         // can grow to 20 under load
        executor.setQueueCapacity(100);      // queue up to 100 tasks
        executor.setThreadNamePrefix("notifications-");  // name in logs
        executor.setKeepAliveSeconds(60);    // idle threads kept for 60s
        executor.initialize();
        return executor;
    }

    @Bean(name = "reportExecutor")
    public Executor reportExecutor() {
        ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
        executor.setCorePoolSize(2);  // reports are heavy — limit threads
        executor.setMaxPoolSize(5);
        executor.setQueueCapacity(20);
        executor.setThreadNamePrefix("reports-");
        executor.initialize();
        return executor;
    }
}

// Use a specific executor by name:
@Async("notificationExecutor")  // uses notificationExecutor
void sendNotification(String userId) { ... }

@Async("reportExecutor")        // uses reportExecutor
CompletableFuture<Report> generateReport(String month) { ... }
```

concept_explanation.scheduled:
**@Scheduled — run code on a schedule:**

```java
import org.springframework.scheduling.annotation.EnableScheduling;
import org.springframework.scheduling.annotation.Scheduled;

// On main class or config:
@EnableScheduling  // activates @Scheduled

@Component
public class ScheduledJobs {

    // Fixed rate: every 30 seconds from application start:
    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 30_000)
    public void refreshPriceCache() {
        priceCache.refresh();
        log.info("Price cache refreshed at " + LocalDateTime.now());
    }

    // Fixed delay: wait 60s AFTER previous execution completes:
    @Scheduled(fixedDelay = 60_000)
    public void processPaymentQueue() {
        paymentQueue.processNext();
        // If this takes 10s, next run starts 60s after it finishes
        // With fixedRate, overlap is possible if job takes longer than rate
    }

    // Cron expression: precise scheduling:
    @Scheduled(cron = "0 0 8 * * MON-FRI")   // 8:00 AM weekdays
    public void sendDailyMarketSummary() {
        marketSummaryService.send();
    }

    @Scheduled(cron = "0 30 17 * * MON-FRI")  // 5:30 PM weekdays (market close)
    public void runEodSettlement() {
        settlementService.process();
    }

    // Initial delay: wait 5s after startup before first run:
    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 10_000, initialDelay = 5_000)
    public void healthCheck() { ... }
}
```

